  "method": "cap",
  "template": "sectioned",
  "summary_text": "Chief Complaint\nReports back pain, particularly on the left.\n\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports experiencing back pain, primarily on the left side, for several weeks. He describes the pain as intermittent, sometimes sharp, sometimes dull, and occasionally moving. He notes that the pain is not always consistent, sometimes present, sometimes absent. He also reports increased fatigue and an uncharacteristic increase in urination at night, necessitating more frequent trips to the restroom. He denies any recent trauma or injury. He reports having experienced similar episodes in the past, including frequent sore throats and 'BFS' (which he doesn't fully understand). He reports riding a bicycle occasionally. He mentions his brother smokes, and he has been told not to smoke, but he doesn't listen. He reports that school is going well, though he struggles with his physics class.\n\nFindings\nPhysical exam reveals no tenderness to palpation of the back, normal range of motion, and no palpable lymphadenopathy. Lung sounds are clear to auscultation. Heart sounds are regular with no murmurs. The patient reports no pain with abdominal palpation. Examination of the throat reveals no erythema or swelling. The patient's tonsils are midline.\n\nAssessment\nThe patient's presentation is concerning for possible musculoskeletal back pain, potentially exacerbated by recurrent strep throat episodes, which may be contributing to glomerular nephritis. Further investigation is warranted to rule out these possibilities.\n\nPlan\nI am ordering a CT scan to evaluate the back pain and to investigate the recurrent strep throat episodes. I am also referring the patient to an ENT specialist to consider a tonsillectomy if indicated. I am ordering a comprehensive laboratory panel including a lipid panel, UA, CMP, CBC, and Vitamin D to assess his overall health and identify any abnormalities. I have scheduled a follow-up appointment in one week to review the results and discuss further management strategies. The patient should return to the clinic if symptoms persist or worsen.",
  "reference_summary": "CHIEF COMPLAINT\n\nBack pain.\n\nMEDICAL HISTORY\n\nPatient reports that he has a frequent history of strep throat with 4 episodes within the last 5 months.\n\nSOCIAL HISTORY\n\nPatient reports that he is a student. He also mentions that he rides his bike every so often and that he is in the process of switching jobs. His new job will be at a restaurant.\n\nFAMILY HISTORY\n\nPatient reports that his siblings are mostly healthy. He does have a brother who smokes while at home.\n\nREVIEW OF SYSTEMS\n\nConstitutional: Denies fatigue or change in appetite.\nGenitourinary: Reports increased urine output.\nMusculoskeletal: Reports left-side back pain.\nEndocrine: Reports increased water consumption\n\nPHYSICAL EXAM\n\nEars, Nose, Mouth, and Throat\n- Examination of Mouth: Normal.\n- Examination of Throat: Pharynx without erythema, swelling, or exudate. Tonsils are midline.\n\nNeck\n- General Examination: Neck is supple without lymphadenopathy. No cervical adenopathy.\n\nRespiratory\n- Auscultation of Lungs: No wheezes, rales, or rhonchi.\n\nCardiovascular\n- Auscultation of Heart: No murmurs, gallops or rubs.\n\nGastrointestinal\n- Examination of Abdomen: No tenderness. No rebound or guarding.\n\nMusculoskeletal\n- Examination: No back tenderness with palpation.\n\nHematology/Lymphatic/Immunology\n- Palpation: No enlarged lymph nodes.\n\nRESULTS\n\nPrevious CT scan is reviewed and demonstrates evidence of swelling potentially related to glomerulonephritis.\n\nASSESSMENT AND PLAN\n\nGlomerulonephritis.\n- Medical Reasoning: The patient presents today with a complaint of back pain, although this was not present on exam today with palpation. He also has a history of recurrent strep throat and a recent CT scan with concerns of possible glomerulonephritis.\n- Patient Education and Counseling: The patient was recommended to watch his salt intake.\n- Medical Treatment: We will refer him to an ENT for further evaluation and treatment. We will also order a lipid panel, UA, CMP, CBC, vitamin D, and a TSH. A work note was provided today as well.\n\nPatient Agreements: The patient understands and agrees with the recommended medical treatment plan.\n\nINSTRUCTIONS\n\nHe will follow up in 1 week via telehealth, however if the results are abnormal this will need to be an in-person visit.",
